pub fn square(index: usize) ChessboardError!u64 {
    if (index < 1 or index > 64) {
        return error.IndexOutOfBounds;
    }
    return 1 << @as(u6, @intCast(index - 1));
}

But shift amount must be integer type that fits. Using @intCast to u6 is fine.

Alternatively, use @as(u64, 1) << (index - 1). But shift amount must be integer type; can use @intCast.

Simplify: return 1 << (index - 1); but shift amount must be compile-time? Not required. But shift amount type must be integer; index - 1 is usize, which is fine.

But shift amount must be less than bit size? Zig runtime checks? Actually shift count is masked for shift on unsigned integers: shift count is masked to lower bits of integer type. For u64, shift count is masked to 6 bits (since 64 bits). So shift count 63 is fine. But shift count 64 would be masked to 0, which would be wrong. But we guard index <=64, so shift count max 63, fine.

